metadata.name: Dencity #836
metadata.description:
Dencity is a generative art project inspired by aerial views of cities with a high density of buildings. Its perspective effect, its perfectly imprecise lines, its subtle textures and its very advanced level of detail give it the appearance of a hand-drawn work.

Behind the visible art (the image) hides another form of art, an extremely complex algorithm capable of calculating and drawing in 2D each variation of the Dencity project. To draw a variation, the algorithm notably takes around 3,000,000 to 20,000,000 random decisions based on the hash of the mint and draws around 800,000 to 4,000,000 lines to create all the strokes and texture effects.

Made with ❤️, code and p5js.

metadata.name: Boundary Conditions #166
metadata.description:
Boundary Conditions is based on a personal observation about the nature of existence: that it is most clear at the interface between two separate aspects of reality. We enjoy the merging of sea and land, congregate at the boundaries of the land and the sky, tenuously ponder—in small, select groups—the limits where atmosphere dwindles into vacuum. Life is about the transition from one state to another, maintaining a precarious existence on the edge of everything.

At the heart of Boundary Conditions is micro-managed Perlin noise, produced as small points and patches of colour. Rendering takes place over three hundred and sixty frames, with the number of points rendered increasing as time passes. This allows the piece to initially form a general overview, and fill in the finer details as time passes. This results in the piece fading gently into view over several seconds, but allows the rendering process to be part of the experience, rather than presenting the viewer with a blank screen or a progress bar.

The main focus of the image is the ‘grains’ layer—the dark, spattered series of grouped dots that form sweeping, striated patterns. A spattering technique is used, as though the grains were splashes of paint flung onto the canvas with vigorous brushstrokes. Amongst them, more saturated and thicker lines of colour accentuate one side of the grains, within certain chosen parameters, like shadows on the sides of a dunes, or the ripples left in sand by the receding tide.

Larger swathes of colour, termed ’dunes’, are added in such a way as to form patches, or thick striations. Along these paths larger circles of ink may be added, sometimes singly, sometimes in a pattern of splashes. Further shading is added to alter shading over the space of the entire instance. The ‘sand’ layer is a tighter, more extreme band of colour, but is intentionally limited so as not to overpower the piece.

Larger geometric shapes are sometimes overlaid: both circles and rectangles. These, too, are stippled in various ways, often fading so that only their corners, or partial edges, are visible.

Rotation is applied, perhaps, at intervals of ninety degrees, or maybe in more subtle ways—sometimes a forty-five degree rotation will produce a diagonal rendering. This is in addition to the rotation of individual blocks, although the two may work against each other, leaving only part of the instance rotated.

The main image produced using the above techniques is taken and used as a building block for the finished piece. It may appear as a background to the entire image, and may then be broken into parts to provide the finished piece. These blocks may be small, may be large, may be further subdivided, or may not even be rendered at all. Sometimes they will be reversed or rotated, sometimes shifted. The grid formations are chosen from a number of sub-styles.

Scaling allows for the image to move beyond the limits of the canvas, or be constrained within it. It also provides the possiblity of a sector being only slightly displaced from the background, leading to something akin to motion-blur. Sometimes a piece will be scaled to extremes of value.

Not all pieces are coloured, and in general the colours are muted and saturation is low. However, the saturation level is variable, and in rare cases can lead to completely greyscale images or, athe other extreme, instances where the saturation values are pushed to twice the standard value. Rarely is a piece saturated to the point where clipping of hue values occurs, but the possiblity is there. A dark mode exists in a small proportion of pieces.

Pressing 'I' whilst the piece is active will bring up an information panel. This will show which render layers are currently available; they can be activated and deactivated using the number keys.

The rendered image, at a resolution of 2048x2048 can be saved with 'S', whilst the actual viewport canvas, at whatever resolution the piece is currently running in, can be saved with 'C'.

'R' and 'P' provide options for re-rendering with and without new parameters.

metadata.name: monuMOments #86
metadata.description:
“monuMOments” was inspired by the work of visual artist Penelope Umbrico, seeking a reflection on the era of techno fossils and on the relationship of human beings with technology and the environment as a whole, whether manufactured or natural.  See more in 

“Penelope Umbrico's MONUMENT explores the monolithic state of current technologies in relation to their obsolescence. Umbrico begins with the idea that all technologies - including the electronics we use at home and in the workplace - are in effect “black boxes” whose contents are largely incomprehensible to end users. Although we tend to think of screens as invisible and we never see the workings of our technologies, almost everything we learn and know these days is mediated through the filters of technology. Umbrico aims to demystify the black-box device and to engage the public in creative modes of transforming and visualizing the electronic detritus that accumulates in our homes and in landfills.” (https://www.bricartsmedia.org).

The algorithm initially simulates the static noise of old televisions and from there on, several elements and layers follow one another that, through different blending modes, colors, lights and shadows, shape the final image.

About the ultra rare feature, CASTING OUT NINES refers to the work of the same name done in 2020 that deals with the largest environmental crime in terms of extension that is known in the country, where hundreds of tons of crude oil were spilled on the coast of northeast Brazil.
Each of the nine photographs in the work represent one of the states reached, where a specific color was superimposed.

The colors superimposed on each of the images appeared by chance, or not so much, and were constructed from temporal data and the location of the appearance of the spots on Brazilian beaches. In the RGB palette of “oil” tones, the value of “R” came from the sum of the tens contained in the date of the first oil record in each of the states, as well as the values of “G” and “B” came from the sum of the numbers contained in the geographic coordinates of latitude and longitude, respectively, of the affected locations.

#Main Features

- 16 color schemes “zones”;
* CASTING OUT NINES – 1,5% chance
* NO SIGNAL – 2% chance
* WOODCUT – 3% chance
* GREY SCALE – 3,5% chance
* TAGs | GOLDEN, SILVER, BRONZE and BLOOD – 4% chance each
* SHAKE + - 6% chance
* SHAKE - - 8% chance
* FRAQUENCIES | 9hz, 10hz, 11hz, 12hz, 13hz and 14hz – 10% chance each
  
- 3 canvas formats;
- 4 rotation frequency;
- 3 degrees of granulometry;

#Royalties split: 30% for minters.

Claimmable physical print: Minters of the ultra rare feature will receive an edition of the book AUGUST TIDE and a collection of 9 exclusive prints (20x12 cm each), numbered and signed, about CASTING OUT NINES.
 
The book and the prints can be claimed by DM on Twitter @morbeck_art or by email contato@mateusmorbeck.com

Other interested parties may purchase separately the book or a printed and signed version of their edition.

June 04, 2022

Generative Token by Morbeck for fxhash.

metadata.name: Crude Acceptance #10
metadata.description:
It was there when we arrived
    No owners, no gatekeepers
    The opportunity to explore
    The chance to transform
    What we are
    What we see
    And a trace will came with us
    And that way it will multiply
    As long as we allow
    To leave here a part of us
    It will be there when we leave
    No owners, no gatekeepers
    But itself



  Controls
  Format:
  'f' - switch square/full screen format

  View:

  'Arrow Up/Down' - Decrease/Increase distance to origin
  'Mouse Drag' - View Rotation


  Export:
  'x' - show/hide export menu
  'm' - quick canvas save


Created with p5.js (Javascript + GLSL) by Victor Doval @vicdoval (2022)
Designed to be seen in Google Chrome 102.0.5005.63

metadata.name: Unicorn #9653
metadata.description:
All of us have dreams, and everyone would like to meet a fairy, a genie, a wizard, or someone else who will make our dreams come true in a snap of a finger or with the wave of a wand. But we're the only ones who can do it. We are those magical unicorns, unique, inimitable, with our own qualities and magical abilities.
These unicorns are the visualization of our inner selves that makes our dreams come true. An embodiment of all the best with a huge positive magical power.
